    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1879-04-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1879-04-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="58"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d58">
                <head>No. 47.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Goodloe</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Evarts</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Brussels</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-04-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 9, 1879</date>. (Received April
                        21.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 56.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The diplomatic relations between Belgium and
                    Mexico which have been interrupted since the death of the Emperor Maximilian
                    (the King’s brother-in-law) are on the point of being resumed. In the budget of
                    the minister for foreign affairs just voted by the chambers was included <pb
                        facs="0186" n="90" xml:id="pg_90"/> a salary for an envoy extraordinary and
                    minister plenipotentiary to the Republic of Mexico. A royal decree has just been
                    promulgated, appointing the Baron Greindl as such minister. He has been in the
                    diplomatic service and is considered here as an accomplished and learned
                    gentleman. He is now awaiting orders, but informed me a few evenings since that
                    he expected to start for his post of duty in May or June, and hoped to be able
                    to go through the United States on his way.</p>
                <p>At least a hope of reviving Belgian commerce (which has been falling off of late
                    years) was, I think, the chief motive in creating this mission, and the proposed
                    Mexican Exposition in 1880 gave a favorable occasion.</p>
                <p>I shall very soon forward you some of the views held by Belgian statesmen in
                    relation to the increase of the consular service, which they hope will be
                    conducive, at no distant day, to an expansion of commerce, by the opening of new
                    channels for Belgian products.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WM. CASSIUS GOODLOE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
